EXPERIMENT 2

AIM:
To design and simulate a Common Source (CS) amplifier with an active load using 180 nm CMOS technology, and to analyze the performance of the circuit using:

1)DC Operating Point Analysis
2)Transient Analysis
3)AC Small Signal Analysis

using LTspice simulation tool
GIVEN: 
VDD ​= 1.2V
P <= 0.4mW
CL ​= 0.5pF
Ln ​= 360nm

DC ANALYSIS:
DC analysis is carried out to determine the operating point (Q-point) of the MOS transistors in the Common Source amplifier with active load. 
Establishing a proper DC bias is important because it ensures that the transistors operate in the saturation region, which is necessary for linear amplification.

In LTspice, the DC operating point is obtained using the .op command, which calculates all node voltages and device currents when the circuit reaches steady state.

This analysis helps in:
  Determining the drain current of the MOS transistors
  Verifying that the devices operate in the saturation region
  Observing the output voltage level
  Confirming that the circuit satisfies the power constraints

Determination of Drain Current:
The maximum allowable drain current is determined from the given power constraint.
  P = VDD​×ID
  ID ​= P / VDD
  ID​ = 0.4×10^−3 / 1.2
  ID​ = 333.3uA
To maintain a safety margin and prevent exceeding the power limit, the drain current is selected as
  ID = 150uA

NMOS Transistor Design (M1):
Vout = VDD / 2 + IDRs    (VRS = IDRs = 0.2V)
     = 1.2 / 2 + 0.2
     = 0.8V
Rs = VRS / ID  =  0.2 / 150e^-6
   = 1333.33ohm

VB1 = VGS1 + IDRs
Assume VOV = 0.25V  , Vth = 0.36V
    VOV = VGS1 - 0.36
    VGS = 0.61V
VB1 = 0.61 + 0.2
    = 0.81V

check for the saturation condition:
    VDS >= VGS1 - VTH
    0.6 > 0.25
Saturation region satisfied for M1 (NMOS)

For the NMOS transistor operating in saturation, the drain current is given by
    ID = 1/2(kn'(W/L)(VGS - VT)e2)
    W = 2IDL / UnCox(VGS - VT)²
NOW, kn' = UnCox
    = Un*epsilon/tox
    = 273.809e-4*epsilon0*3.9/4.1e-9
    = 2.306e-4
VOV ​= 0.25V
the width of the NMOS transistor is calculated. From the design calculations
  WM1 = 3.750um

PMOS Active Load Design (M2):

VOV = 0.25V
|VTH| = 0.3920V

VOV = VSG - |VTH|
VSG >> VOV + VTH
       0.25 + 0.39
       0.64V

VSG = VS - VG
VG = VS - VSG
   = 1.2 - 0.64
VG = 0.54

the width of the PMOS transistor is calculated. From the design calculations
    ID = 1/2(kn'(W/L)(VGS - VT)e2)
    W = 2IDL / UnCox(VGS - VT)²
NOW, kn' = UnCox
         = Un*epsilon/tox
      Un = 115.4e^-4
     kn' = 9.735e^-5

W = 17.75 um

![Circuit Diagram](https://github.com/manjunathyalaburgi-lab/lic-lab/blob/main/lab1%20circuit1.png)

DC Operating Point from Simulation:

DC analysis is performed to determine the operating point (Q-point) of the MOS transistors used in the Common Source amplifier with an active load. 
The main objective of this analysis is to ensure that both the NMOS transistor (M1) and the PMOS transistor (M2) operate in the saturation region, which is necessary for proper amplification.

The DC operating point was verified using the .op command in LTspice.
The obtained simulation results are:
    FOR WIDTH 
    WM1 = 39um
    WM2 = 44um
    ID = 150.808uA
    Vout = 0.80592V

![Circuit Diagram](https://github.com/manjunathyalaburgi-lab/lic-lab/blob/main/lab2%20circuit1%20DC.png)

TRANSIENT ANALYSIS:

Transient analysis is performed to observe the time-domain behavior of the amplifier when a time-varying input signal is applied. 
This analysis helps in understanding how the circuit responds to real signals and verifies whether the amplifier provides proper signal amplification

The transient simulation was carried out in LTspice using the command:.tran 5m

A sinusoidal input signal with a small amplitude was applied to the gate of the NMOS transistor. 
The input signal used in the simulation had the following parameters:
Frequency = 1 kHz
Peak amplitude = 10 mV
Peak-to-peak input voltage = 20 mV
The transient response of the circuit shows that the output waveform is amplified and inverted with respect to the input signal, which is the expected behavior of a Common Source amplifier.

Gain Calculation from Transient Simulation:
From the waveform obtained in LTspice:
Vout(p-p) = 913.380 mV − 659.872mV
Vout(p-p) = 253.507 mV

Input peak-to-peak voltage:
Vin(p-p) = 20 mV

Voltage gain:

Av = Vout / Vin
Av = 225.514 / 20
Av = 12.6753

Gain in decibels:

Gain(dB) = 20 log10(Av)
Gain(dB) = 20 log10(12.6753)
Gain(dB) ≈ 22.058 dB

Thus, the transient analysis confirms that the circuit provides significant voltage amplification with phase inversion, 
validating the operation of the Common Source amplifier.
![Circuit Diagram](https://github.com/manjunathyalaburgi-lab/lic-lab/blob/main/lab2%20circuit1%20transient%20Vout.png)
![Circuit Diagram](https://github.com/manjunathyalaburgi-lab/lic-lab/blob/main/lab2%20circuit1%20transient%20Vin.png)

AC ANALYSIS:

AC analysis is performed to study the frequency response of the amplifier. 
It helps determine important parameters such as mid-band gain, bandwidth, and the −3 dB cutoff frequency.
In LTspice, AC analysis was carried out using the command: .ac dec 100 0.1 100G
This command sweeps the frequency across a wide range and plots the gain of the amplifier in decibels (dB).

Mid-Band Gain

From the flat region of the AC magnitude plot, the gain of the amplifier is approximately:
Gain = 22.1149 dB
This represents the mid-band gain where the amplifier provides maximum amplification.

Bandwidth Calculation:
The bandwidth of the amplifier is determined from the −3 dB point of the gain curve.
−3 dB = 19.1149
From the AC response plot:
Bandwidth = 99.10 MHz
This frequency corresponds to the point where the gain drops by 3 dB from the mid-band value.

Interpretation:
The AC analysis shows that the amplifier maintains a relatively constant gain across the mid-frequency region and begins to decrease at higher frequencies due to parasitic capacitances and device limitations.

The obtained bandwidth indicates that the amplifier can operate effectively over a wide range of frequencies, making it suitable for high-speed analog applications.
![Circuit Diagram](https://github.com/manjunathyalaburgi-lab/lic-lab/blob/main/lab2%20circuit1%20Ac.png)
![Circuit Diagram](https://github.com/manjunathyalaburgi-lab/lic-lab/blob/main/lab2%20circuit1%20Ac%20-3dB.png)

RESULT:

The Common Source amplifier with an active PMOS load was successfully designed and simulated using 180 nm CMOS technology in LTspice. 
The DC operating point analysis confirmed that the NMOS and PMOS transistors operate in the saturation region, ensuring proper biasing of the amplifier. The simulated drain current was approximately 150.8 µA, and the output voltage was observed to be around 0.806 V, which closely matches the calculated theoretical values.

Transient analysis showed that the output signal was amplified and inverted with respect to the input signal, 
verifying the expected behavior of a Common Source amplifier. From the transient waveform, the voltage gain was calculated to be approximately 11.27 V/V, corresponding to about 21.04 dB.

AC analysis was performed to study the frequency response of the circuit. The mid-band gain obtained from the AC magnitude plot was approximately 19.11 dB. 
The −3 dB bandwidth of the amplifier was observed to be around 99.10 MHz, indicating that the amplifier can operate effectively over a wide range of frequencies.

Overall, the simulation results are in good agreement with the theoretical design calculations.


INFERENCE

From this experiment, the design and performance of a Common Source amplifier using CMOS technology were studied and verified through simulation. 
The DC analysis ensured that the MOS transistors were correctly biased in the saturation region, which is essential for linear amplification.

The transient analysis confirmed that the amplifier provides voltage gain with a 180° phase inversion,
which is a characteristic feature of the Common Source configuration. The AC analysis demonstrated the frequency response of the circuit and showed that the amplifier achieves a stable gain and a wide bandwidth.

The close agreement between theoretical calculations and LTspice simulation results validates the design methodology used for the amplifier. 
This experiment demonstrates the practical implementation of MOSFET amplifiers and highlights their importance in analog integrated circuit design.


